{"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "Question", "name": "Equality Model or Nordic Model of Prostitution Explained", "text": "What is the Equality Model?", "description": "The Equality Model is the partial decriminalization of sex work while leaving both the purchase and promotion of prostitution illegal. Unequivocal evidence shows that the Equality Model is not in the best interest of sex workers.", "url": "https://decriminalizesex.work/why-decriminalization/", "eduQuestionType": "Comparison", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The Equality Model criminalizes the buying of sex but not the selling of sex, assumes sex workers need to be 'saved', does not decrease exploitation in the commercial sex industry, and makes sex workers financially dependent on criminalized clients."}, "suggestedAnswer": [{"@type": "Answer", "text": "Decriminalization of Sex Work reduces violence and exploitation, is recommended by Amnesty International and the World Health Organization, improves sex worker health and safety, and empowers sex workers to operate independently."}], "review": {"@type": "Review", "reviewBody": "There is irony in using the term 'equality' to describe prostitution laws that criminalize only one side of a sex work transaction. The implementation of laws that criminalize clients clearly correlates with an increase in violence perpetrated against sex workers.", "reviewRating": {"@type": "Rating", "ratingValue": "1"}}, "author": {"@type": "Organization", "name": "Decriminalize Sex Work", "url": "https://decriminalizesex.work/"}, "datePublished": "2021-10-01", "image": "https://i0.wp.com/decriminalizesex.work/wp-content/uploads/Equality-Model-or-Nordic-Model-of-Prostitution-Explained.jpg?ssl=1"}